cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use AMP, please cite it as below."
title: "Agent Memory Protocol (AMP): A vendor-neutral wire format for agent memory operations"
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: "M. Thamil"
    given-names: "M."
    email: "mthamil107@gmail.com"
version: 0.0.0
date-released: 2026-05-26
url: "https://github.com/mthamil107/agent-memory-protocol"
repository-code: "https://github.com/mthamil107/agent-memory-protocol"
license: Apache-2.0
keywords:
  - agent
  - memory
  - protocol
  - vendor-neutral
  - governance
  - RAG
  - vector-store
  - MCP
abstract: >-
  Agent Memory Protocol (AMP) is a vendor-neutral wire format and reference
  implementation for agent memory operations. It defines five operations
  (remember, recall, forget, merge, expire) over four memory types (semantic,
  episodic, procedural, emotional), a `MemoryStore` protocol that any backend
  can implement, and an optional governance channel for human-in-the-loop
  diff-and-approve review of writes. AMP composes above existing memory
  frameworks (mem0, Letta, Cognee, Zep, sqlite-vec, pgvector) rather than
  replacing them, with a memory router that fans operations across stores and
  fuses recall results via Reciprocal Rank Fusion (k=60) with an optional
  one-hop graph boost.
